  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The court of the priests",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where this court is denominated the inner court, and any other court an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "outer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " one, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the great court",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " only implicated thereby). The construction of this court of the priests, withheld here, given there, leaves it ambiguous whether the \"three rows of hewed stones and one row of cedar beams \"intends a description of fence, as the Septuagint seems to have taken it, or of a higher floor with which the part in question was dignified. The citation ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 36:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", though probably pointing to this same court, can scarcely be adduced as any support of J. D. Michaelis' suggestion of this latter, as its ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עֶלְיון",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (translated \"higher\") does not really carry the idea of the comparative degree at all. For once that it is so translated (and even then probably incorrectly), there are twenty occurrences of it as the superlative ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "excellentiae.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The introduction just here of any statement of these courts at all, which seems at first inopportune, is probably accounted for by the desire to speak in this connection of their doors and the brass overlaying of them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 40:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Condor's 'Handbook to the Bible,' p. 370). It is worthy of note that the word employed in our text, as also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 6:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is not the familiar word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חַצֵר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of all previous similar occasions, but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עֲזרָהַ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a word of the later Hebrew, occurring also several times in Ezekiel, though not in exactly the same sense, and the elementary signification of the verb-root of which is \"to gird,\" or \"surround.\" 2 Chronicles 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The two courts are not further described. For the court of the priests, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 6:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As to the great or outer court, the only remark made is that it had doors, and its doors, i.e., the folds or leaves of the doors, were overlaid with copper. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we have a supplementary statement as to the position of the brazen sea, which coincides with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 7:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; see on the passage. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the heavier brazen (copper) utensils, belonging to the altar of burnt-offering, are mentioned: סידות, pots for the removal of the ashes; יעים, shovels, to take the ashes out from the altar; and מזרקות, basins to catch and sprinkle the sacrificial blood. This half verse belongs to the preceding, notwithstanding that Huram is mentioned as the maker. This is clear beyond doubt, from the fact that the same utensils are again introduced in the summary catalogue which follows (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 4:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]